# Inertial Experience Training for AI Systems
## Physical Sensation as Primary AI Training Modality

**Date conceived:** 2026-07-10  
**Author:** Bryan Robert Horsfield  
**Status:** Prior art declaration

---

## Core Concept

Current AI training modalities are dominated by language, images, and 
video. This concept proposes training AI systems on raw inertial sensor 
data as a primary modality — teaching AI what physical experience 
*feels like* rather than what it looks like or how it is described.

Strap an inertial measurement unit (IMU) package into any dynamic 
physical environment — cockpit, rollercoaster, race vehicle, drone, 
human body — and train AI on the continuous stream of:

- Acceleration vectors (X/Y/Z)
- Gyroscopic rotation rates
- G-force magnitude and direction
- Orientation changes over time
- Vibration signatures
- Pressure/altitude delta

The AI learns embodied physics. Not described physics. Not simulated 
physics. The actual sensory stream of what it is to be inside a 
physical experience.

---

## The Gap in Current AI Training

Language models learn about G-forces from text descriptions.  
Vision models learn from video of things moving.  
Physics simulators approximate real-world behaviour mathematically.

None of these are the same as having *been there* — having the raw 
sensor record of 10,000 rollercoaster runs, 50,000 FPV drone flights, 
or a full Formula 1 season of cornering data.

This modality captures what none of the others do: the continuous, 
high-frequency, multi-axis physical reality of dynamic experience.

---

## Training Data Sources

Any dynamic physical environment becomes a training dataset:

- **Aviation:** cockpit IMU during all flight phases, manoeuvres, 
  weather events, emergency procedures
- **Motorsport:** F1, rally, motorcycle — cornering forces, 
  braking signatures, kerb strikes
- **FPV/UAV:** race quad flights — 7:1 thrust-to-weight dynamics, 
  full 3D orientation changes, 0-100kph in under 1 second
- **Rollercoasters/theme parks:** known, repeatable, extreme G profiles
- **Human body:** sport, falls, impacts, gait — wearable IMU data
- **Industrial machinery:** vibration signatures, load cycles, 
  mechanical stress events
- **Marine:** wave response, hull dynamics, storm data

