## Applications

### Anomaly Detection
An AI trained on 10,000 hours of normal flight *knows* what normal 
feels like at a sensor level. Deviations from learned inertial 
signatures flag mechanical issues, structural problems, or abnormal 
conditions before they become critical.

Not rule-based threshold alerts — genuine learned understanding of 
normal vs abnormal physical state.

### Predictive Maintenance
Machinery develops characteristic inertial signatures as components 
wear. An AI trained on healthy vs degraded equipment learns to 
detect degradation from vibration and motion data alone — before 
failure, not after.

### Simulator Fidelity
Flight simulators, driving simulators, and training systems currently 
approximate physics mathematically. An AI trained on real inertial 
data can validate and correct simulator behaviour — "this doesn't 
feel like the real thing" becomes a trainable, measurable property.

### Autonomous Vehicle Control
Vehicles that understand physics through inertial experience rather 
than purely through vision. The system knows what a skid feels like, 
what aquaplaning feels like, what a tyre blowout feels like — from 
sensor data, not from rules.

### Human Performance and Safety
Wearable IMU training data from elite athletes — the AI learns what 
peak human physical performance looks like at a sensor level. 
Applications in coaching, injury prevention, rehabilitation, and 
detecting falls or medical events in real time.

### Robotics
Robots trained on inertial data from human movement learn natural 
motion patterns — not programmed trajectories but the actual 
physics of how humans move through space. Combines naturally with 
the hydraulic expansion chamber actuator system (see separate file) 
where circuit pressure IS the inertial feedback.

