## Key Distinction from Existing Work

Inertial data exists in:
- Flight data recorders (black boxes) — collected but not used as 
  AI training modality
- IMU logging in research — used for specific task analysis
- Physics simulation — mathematical approximation, not real data

**What does not appear to exist:**
Training an AI on raw continuous multi-axis inertial data streams 
as a *primary modality* — equivalent in scope and intent to how 
language models are trained on text — to develop generalised 
understanding of physical experience across domains.

The modality itself is the novelty. Not the sensors. Not the data. 
The training approach that treats inertial experience as a 
first-class input equivalent to language or vision.

---

## Implementation Notes

- Consumer-grade IMU packages (MPU-6050 etc) sufficient for 
  proof of concept
- High-frequency logging (1kHz+) captures full dynamic range
- Multi-sensor fusion (IMU + barometer + magnetometer) for 
  complete spatial picture
- Dataset labelling: environment type, event markers, outcome data
- Training architecture: time-series transformer or similar 
  sequential model suited to continuous sensor streams

---

## Prior Art Statement

To the best of the author's knowledge, no existing system treats 
raw multi-axis inertial sensor streams as a primary AI training 
modality — analogous to how text is the primary modality for 
language models — for the purpose of teaching AI systems 
generalised understanding of physical experience.

This document establishes the date of conception and sufficient 
technical detail to constitute prior art.

